## Day 01 — Time and Space Complexity

Today I learned about Big-O notation. Before today I used to just
write code that gives the correct answer. I never thought about
how fast it runs or how much memory it uses. Today that changed.

### What I understood

Big-O is basically asking one question — if my input becomes very
large, how does my code behave? Does it slow down a little or a lot?

For example if I have 1 million elements in a list:
- O(1) code still does just 1 step
- O(n) code does 1 million steps
- O(n²) code does 1 trillion steps and will practically freeze

That example made it very clear to me why complexity matters.

### The order I memorized

O(1) → O(log n) → O(n) → O(n log n) → O(n²) → O(2ⁿ)

Left side is fast. Right side is slow. Always try to stay on the left.

### How I identify complexity by looking at code

If there is no loop → O(1)  
If there is one loop → O(n)  
If there are two nested loops → O(n²)  
If input is halved each step like binary search → O(log n)  
If there are two separate loops (not nested) → still O(n)  

The two separate loops one confused me at first. I thought it would
be O(n²) but it is actually O(n) + O(n) = O(2n) = O(n) because
we drop the constant.

### The 4 rules I will use every time

1. Drop constants — O(3n) is just O(n)
2. Drop smaller terms — O(n² + n) is just O(n²)
3. Nested loops multiply — two nested loops = O(n²)
4. Sequential loops add but take the largest — O(n) + O(n²) = O(n²)

### Space complexity

This is about extra memory the code uses. Not the input itself,
only the extra memory I create inside the function.

If I create a new list of size n → O(n) space  
If I only use a few variables → O(1) space  
If I use recursion → the call stack also takes O(n) space  

I used to never think about space. Now I will always ask both:
what is the time and what is the space.

### The mistake I made today

I thought sets are fast because they store only unique elements.
That is wrong. Sets are fast because of hashing. Hashing lets the
set jump directly to where the element would be without checking
every element one by one.

So `x in my_list` is O(n) — checks every element  
And `x in my_set` is O(1) — hashing jumps directly  

This is one of the most important things I learned today.

### Python built-ins I now know the complexity of

| Operation | Complexity |
|-----------|------------|
| list[i] | O(1) |
| list.append(x) | O(1) |
| list.insert(0, x) | O(n) |
| x in list | O(n) |
| x in set | O(1) |
| dict[key] | O(1) |
| len(list) | O(1) |

### Problems I solved today

**LC 1480 — Running Sum of 1D Array**  
At first I created a new result list and appended the running total.
That gave me O(n) time and O(n) space.  
Then I realized I can just modify the input array itself and save
that extra space. Final solution is O(n) time and O(1) space.

**LC 1732 — Find the Highest Altitude**  
I just kept a running total of altitude and tracked the maximum.
Only two variables needed. O(n) time and O(1) space.

### How I will apply this going forward

Every single time I write a solution from now, before I submit it
I will ask myself three questions:

1. What is the time complexity?
2. What is the space complexity?
3. Can I do better?

This is also what interviewers ask. So I want to make it a habit
from day one itself.


The only thing I got slightly wrong was the reason why sets are
fast. I said it is because of uniqueness but the real reason is
hashing. I will not forget this again.

